items.title: Health benefits of olives and olive oil
items.summary: A research team discovered that the olive-derived compound oleuropein helps prevent type 2 diabetes.

items.title: Predicting atypical development in infants at high risk for autism?
items.summary: New research identifies a potential biomarker that predicts atypical development in 1- to 2-month-old infants at high versus low familial risk for developing autism spectrum disorders (ASD).

alternate.title: Predicting atypical development in infants at high risk for autism?

items.title: How hibernating ribosomes wake up
items.summary: Scientists have uncovered the way a bacterial ribosome moves from an inactive to an active form, and how that 'wake up call' is key to its survival.

items.title: 'Superbug' bacteria gang up on us, fueled by antibiotic use, nursing home study suggests
items.summary: What's worse than getting exposed to a kind of bacteria that modern antibiotics can't kill? Getting exposed to more than one -- because they may work together to cause an infection, new research suggests. And trying different antibiotics to control one such 'superbug' may only encourage others. The researchers say it's time to think about such bacteria as members of an antibiotic-resistant ecosystem in healthcare environments -- not as single species that act and respond alone.

alternate.title: 'Superbug' bacteria gang up on us, fueled by antibiotic use, nursing home study suggests

items.title: Microscope invented at marine biological laboratory illuminates chromosomal 'dark matter'
items.summary: Biologists, instrument developers, and computational scientists have for the first time measured the density of a relatively inscrutable, highly condensed form of chromosomal material (heterochromatin) that appears in the cells of human beings and other eukaryotes.

alternate.title: Microscope invented at marine biological laboratory illuminates chromosomal 'dark matter'
